Contextually, one then wonders whether Senate decisions have any import. Instructively, EACC’s decision was based on his impeachment. Logically, IEBC would be expected to follow suit since it partly relies on EACC’s word as far as the requirements of Chapter Six of the Constitution go.
But should Mr Havi’s position prevail, as ably canvassed by reference to precedence, then the net implication is that both the EACC and IEBC have a mere ceremonial role in the war against corruption. Consequently, their decision to bar anyone from contesting amounts to naught.
Most importantly, it brings to question the significance of impeachment. Can superior courts overturn an impeachment? What does this portend, considering that the Senate is independent and impartial — at least as per the Constitution?



