Integrity scale
Arguably, Chapter Six complicates the issue. One of the guiding principles of leadership and integrity (Article 73, clause 2(a)), for instance, implies that elected leaders need not be people of integrity: “Selection on the basis of personal integrity, competence and suitability, or election in free and fair elections.”
Seemingly, state officers, who are appointed, are subject to the integrity scale but those to be elected are deemed special, with their integrity being pegged on free and fair elections!
I may be wrong; I am not a legal expert. But I wouldn’t be the only one with a different view. Prof Kithure Kindiki, a lawyer and Tharaka Nithi senator, is of the opinion that the likes of Waititu and Sonko need be barred from contesting. Evidently, the law is never ‘very clear’ after all.
Voters have a critical role of putting the right people into office. Thanks to equivocal laws, we are likely to have all kinds of shady characters on the ballot, yet we may not rely on the concerned state agencies to sieve the dregs from the long cast of aspirants.
Implicitly, the voter remains our only hope. Should they abdicate this noble duty, expect another avalanche of clownish, clueless and corrupt office holders in the name of “elected leaders”.



